'''Adriana Inés Acosta''' ([[Lomas de Zamora]], 19 January 1956 – disappeared on 27 May 1978 in [[Buenos Aires]]) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[activism|militant]] and [[field hockey]] player who was [[Forced disappearance#Argentina|kidnapped]] by the [[National Reorganization Process|military dictatorship]] that ruled Argentina from 1976 to 1983. On 1972 she integrated and was captain of the metropolitan champion youth team [[Lomas Athletic Club]]. On 1973 she was captain of the Buenos Aires team that won the Argentine championship. She also integrated the youth and the [[Argentina women's national field hockey team|national field hockey team]].<ref>[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/deportes/8-73850-2006-10-01.html Una Leona, treinta años antes] {{es icon}}</ref> During the dictatorship that took the power on 1976, she maintained a militancy against the regime. She was kidnapped on 27 May 1978, when she was 22 years old, and was taken to the [[clandestine detention center]] known as El Banco. She is still missing since then.
In her memory, the field hockey court in the [[CeNARD]], has her name.<ref>[http://tiempo.infonews.com/notas/siempre-estuvo-cerca Siempre estuvo cerca] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224111809/http://tiempo.infonews.com/notas/siempre-estuvo-cerca |date=December 24, 2013 }} {{es icon}}</ref><ref>[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/deportes/8-133028-2009-10-07.html La cancha de hockey de la memoria] {{es icon}}</ref>
