[[File:John Dewey in 1902.jpg|thumb|right|Pragmatic ethics was discussed by [[John Dewey]] (pictured)]] '''Pragmatic ethics''' is a theory of [[normative ethics|normative]] [[Philosophy|philosophical]] [[ethics]]. Ethical pragmatists such as [[John Dewey]] believe that some societies have progressed [[morality|morally]] in much the way they have attained progress in [[science]]. Scientists can pursue [[inquiry]] into the [[truth]] of a [[hypothesis]] and [[belief|accept]] the hypothesis, in the sense that they act as though the hypothesis were true; nonetheless, they think that future generations can advance science, and thus future generations can refine or replace (at least some of) their accepted hypotheses. Similarly, ethical pragmatists think that norms, principles, and moral criteria are likely to be improved as a result of [[inquiry]].

==Contrast with other normative theories<!--'Peircean realism' redirects here-->==
Much as it is appropriate for scientists to act as though a hypothesis were true despite expecting future inquiry to supplant it, ethical pragmatists acknowledge that it can be appropriate to practice a variety of other normative approaches (e.g. [[consequentialism]], [[deontological ethics]], and [[virtue ethics]]), yet acknowledge the need for mechanisms which allow society to advance beyond such approaches, a freedom for discourse which does not take any such theory as assumed.<ref name=Liszka>{{cite web |url= http://www.american-philosophy.org/archives/past_conference_programs/pc2005/Liszka.htm |title= What Is Pragmatic Ethics? |first= James |last= Liszka | accessdate= 2011-07-01}}</ref> Thus, aimed at [[social innovation]], the ''practice'' of pragmatic ethics supplements the practice of other normative approaches with what [[John Stuart Mill]] called "experiments of living".<ref name=Mill1863>{{harvtxt|Mill|1863}}</ref>

Pragmatic ethics also differs from other normative approaches ''theoretically'', according to {{harvtxt|Lafollette|2000}}:<ref name="Lafollette2000"/>

# It focuses on society, rather than on lone individuals, as the entity which achieves morality.<ref name=Lafollette2000>{{harvtxt|Lafollette|2000}}</ref> In Dewey's words, "all conduct is ... social." <ref name=Dewey1922>{{harvtxt| Dewey|1922}}</ref>
# It does not hold any known moral criteria as beyond potential for revision.<ref name=Lafollette2000/> Pragmatic ethics may be misunderstood as [[Moral relativism|relativist]], as failing to be objective, but that is like suggesting that science fails to be objective. Ethical pragmatists, like scientists, can maintain that their endeavor is objective on the grounds that it converges towards something objective (a thesis called '''Peircean realism'''<!--boldface per WP:R#PLA-->).<ref name="Almeder1983">{{cite journal |last= Almeder |first= R. |year=1983 |title= Scientific Progress and Peircean Utopian Realism |journal= Erkenntnis |issue= 20 |pages= 253–280}}</ref>
# It allows that a moral judgment may be appropriate in one age of a given society, even though it will cease to be appropriate after that society progresses (or may already be inappropriate in another society).<ref name=Lafollette2000/> For example, the writings of [[Thomas Jefferson]] [[Thomas Jefferson and slavery|on slavery]] framed slavery as ultimately immoral, yet temporarily moral until America was ready for abolition.<ref name="HEI">{{cite book | last = Bateman | first = Newton |author2=Paul Selby |author3=Frances M. Shonkwiler |author4=Henry L Fowkes  | title = Historical Encyclopedia of Illinois | publisher = Munsell Publishing Company | year = 1908 | location = Chicago, IL | page = 259}}</ref>

==Relationship to pragmatism==
Establishing that this normative theory entails [[pragmatism]] (or vice versa) remains an open challenge. The ''Blackwell Guide to Ethical Theory'' refers to this theory as pragmatic and finds it in the writings of [[John Dewey]] (a pragmatist). However, it also finds key concepts in the writings of [[John Stuart Mill]] and [[Martha Nussbaum]],<ref name=Lafollette2000/> and we can see at least some of its distinguishing characteristics in the concept of [[social gadfly]] attributed to [[Socrates]] in [[Plato|Plato's]] ''[[Apology (Plato)|Apology]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Plat.Apol.30e&lang=original | title = Apology 30e}}</ref>

==Criticisms==
Pragmatic ethics has been criticized as conflating [[descriptive ethics]]  with [[normative ethics]], as describing the way people ''do'' make moral judgments rather than the way they ''should'' make them. While some ethical pragmatists may have questioned the distinction between normative and descriptive truth, the theory of pragmatic ethics itself does not conflate them any more than science conflates truth about its subject matter with current opinion about it.<ref name=Liszka/>

==Moral ecology==
Moral ecology is a variation of pragmatic ethics which additionally supposes that morality evolves like an [[ecosystem]], and ethical practice should therefore include strategies analogous to those of [[ecosystem management]] (e.g. protecting a degree of moral diversity). The term "moral ecology" has been used since at least 1985 to imply a [[symbiosis]] whereby the viability of any existing moral approach would be diminished by the destruction of all alternative approaches.<ref name=Bellah1985>{{harvtxt|Bellah|1985}}</ref><ref name= Hertzke1998>{{harvtxt| Hertzke |1998}}</ref> According to Tim Dean, current scientific evidence confirms that humans do take diverse approaches to morality, and such [[Polymorphism (biology)|polymorphism]] gives humanity [[Resilience (ecology)|resilience]] against a wider range of situations and environments (which makes moral diversity a natural consequence of [[frequency-dependent selection]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=   http://unsworks.unsw.edu.au/fapi/datastream/unsworks:12763/SOURCE02?view=true |last1 = Dean | first1 = Tim |title= Evolution & Moral Ecology | year = 2014 }}</ref> 
<ref name=Dean2012>{{Cite journal | last1 = Dean | first1 = T. | title = Evolution and Moral Diversity | doi = 10.4148/biyclc.v7i0.1775 | journal = The Baltic International Yearbook of Cognition, Logic and Communication | volume = 7 | year = 2012 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>

